briefTitle: A Study to Evaluate the Efficacy of Investigational OTC Eye Drops

outcomeMeasures.title: Clinician Assessment of Change From Baseline in Redness at 60 Seconds After First Product Application
outcomeMeasures.description: Mean change from baseline in redness. Redness was assessed on a 5-point severity scale with 0.5 increments (0 = none, 1 = mild, 2 = moderate, 3 = severe, and 4 = extremely severe), where a lower score is better.

outcomeMeasures.title: Percentage of Participants With Response to Redness at 60 Seconds After First Product Application
outcomeMeasures.description: The responder was defined as a subject whose assessment score at 60 seconds after the initial eye drop is less than the assessment score at baseline. Redness was assessed on a 5-point severity scale with 0.5 increments (0 = none, 1 = mild, 2 = moderate, 3 = severe, and 4 = extremely severe), where a lower score is better.

outcomeMeasures.description: Redness was assessed on a 5-point severity scale with 0.5 increments (0 = none, 1 = mild, 2 = moderate, 3 = severe, and 4 = extremely severe), where a lower score is better.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Ocular Comfort at 60 Seconds After First Product Application
outcomeMeasures.description: Ocular comfort was assessed on an 11-point visual analog scale (0-10) where 0 = very uncomfortable and 10 = very comfortable, where a higher score was better.

outcomeMeasures.title: My Eye Feels Hydrated - Baseline
